Multi-A-Z versus read replicas.

These are the two R-D-S features that look similar and solve completely different problems. Multi-A-Z provisions a synchronous standby in a different availability zone in the same region. Every write commits to both the primary and the standby before the application sees an acknowledgement. The standby carries no traffic; it sits idle as a hot spare. When the primary fails, R-D-S detects it, promotes the standby, and flips the D-N-S record on the database endpoint, so the application reconnects to the same endpoint name and lands on the new primary. Typical failover is sixty to a hundred twenty seconds. Its whole purpose is high availability, not capacity. The newer Multi-A-Z D-B Cluster variant runs one writer plus two readable standbys across three zones, giving H-A plus a little read scaling, with failover often under thirty-five seconds.

Read Replicas are asynchronous copies that do serve read traffic, up to five per source, or fifteen for Aurora. Each has its own endpoint, so the application must be written to send reads there. Replicas can be cross-region, which is also a D-R option, and they can be promoted to a standalone primary. Because replication is asynchronous, replicas can lag; that's fine for reporting and analytics, but wrong when you need read-after-write consistency.

The one-line split: Multi-A-Z is availability, meaning synchronous, an idle standby, and the same endpoint. Read Replicas are read scaling, meaning asynchronous, active, and a separate endpoint. And they're often used together: Multi-A-Z for high availability, and read replicas for read fan-out.
